725191f-d.title: Queens: 30th Road - Vernon Boulevard
725191f-d.text:
30th Road, south side, between Vernon Boulevard and 12th
Street, showing the General Ebenezer Stevens mansion, also
known as the Albert Gallatin House. The two houses shown,
formerly comprised one mansion which was cut in two parts and
moved apart. The house was built in 1800 and when General
Stevens took up his residenoe here he named the place ''Vount
Napoleon.' The General was a member of the Boston Tea Party
and served throughout the Revolutionary War. He died in 1823.
His son, Kerby Stevens, married a daughter of Albert Gallatin,
United States Secretary of the Treasury under Thomas Jefferson.
Gallatin died in this house in 1849, aged 88.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  View 1: 1922
MAY BE REPRODUCED  View 2: 1923
Views 3,4: 1925

725192f-a.text:

showing the home of General Ebenezer Stevens, an early
eighteenth century structure. This home is also known as
the Albert Gallatin house, in which the noted Secretary of
